24.title: Sinus Pressure
dlg:
If the openings from the sinuses into the nasal passage become blocked, a vacuum within the sinus cavity can lead to negative pressure resulting in sinus pain and pressure.

Sinuses are filled with air and lined with mucus membranes. They produce mucus which cleans and moistens the lining of the nose and throat. The nose allows for free exchange of air and mucus with the sinus.

Usually in a healthy sinus, air and mucus are able to flow between the nasal passages and the sinuses easily.

If mucus blocks the nasal passages due to the small hairs in there not working properly to move mucus out, or if a cold causes too much mucus to be produced and blocks the opening of the sinuses or even if nasal polyps block this openings, you will be looking at a sinus pressure build up.

0.header:
Inflamed sinuses can cause a build up of pressure in the sinus cavities.

Before you see what a pharmacist recommend over the counter for sinus pressure relief, let's make sure it is sinus pressure you are looking at.

1.header: Do you feel tightness and pain behind the eyes?

3.header: What about pounding on the forehead and face?

4.header:
Yes?
Chances you are looking at sinus pressure is getting high.

5.header: Any ear pain and pressure?

6.header:
Yes?
Most likely looking at sinus pressure.

7.header: Does this make it feel like you have a toothache?

8.header:
Yes?
Sinus pressure may make it feel like you have a toothache.

Symptoms include:

  • Tightness and pain behind the eyes.
  • Pounding on the forehead and face
  • Ear pain and pressure.
  • Feeling the tooth ache.

9.header: Are you experiencing pain and pressure across the cheek?

10.header:
Yes?
Possibly looking at sinus pressure.

Let's continue and see how to take care of this.

11.header:
Those were a few signs of a sinus pressure.

Let's see how to take care of this if you think you are experiencing one.

20.header:
Eliminating the cause of this pressure will help provide relief.

Let's see what you are looking at.

21.header: Is the pressure as a result of a cold or flu?

22.header:
Yes?
Cold and flu can produce mucus causing pressure build up in the sinuses.

Continue to make sure the sinuses are not infected since bacterial and other germs can grow more easily in this build up of mucus.

23.header: Is it as a result of allergy to for instance pollens or dust?

25.header:
Alright.
Let's look for signs of infection or inflammation.

27.header: In addition to this sinus pressure, do you also have fever?

28.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Looking at a sinus infection

29.header: Does your face feel tender and swollen with this pressure?

30.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • May be looking at a sinus infection.

31.header: What about headache and a very bad cough especially at night?

32.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Looking at a sinus infection

33.header: Have you lost your sense of smell with this sinus pressure?

35.header: Do you sometimes experience a foul or metallic taste since the sinus pressure started?

36.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Sinus infection possibility.

37.header: Has this sinus pressure thing been going on for longer than 2 weeks?

38.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • The sinuses are going to be infected by now.

39.header:
Those were common symptoms of a sinus infection.

There are other reasons to have pressure in your sinuses besides a sinus infection.

Let's continue if you don't think you are looking at a sinus infection.

If you think you are looking at a sinus infection, you will have to see a doctor. Nothing over the counter will take care of a sinus infection.

40.header:
Have you been diagnosed with nasal polyps in the past?

The symptoms are usually:

  • Nose feeling blocked
  • Reduced or complete loss of sense of smell
  • Runny nose
  • Breathing through the mouth.

41.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • These may have returned.
  • They may block the opening of the sinuses leading to pressure and pain in the sinuses.

42.header:
What about a deviated septum?

Or nasal bone spur?

43.header:
Seek urgent care or a doctor for further evaluation.

Here is why:

  • Need further evaluation. Do not seek self care.

44.header: Did the sinus pressure improve initially for about 3 to 4 days and now is getting worse?

45.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Looking at sinus infection.

46.header:
Alright.
Improving sinus drainage will help relieve some pressure in the sinuses.

Let's see what a pharmacist recommend to help improve sinus drainage and relieve other symptoms accompanying this sinus pain and pressure that is available over the counter.

This will assume you are not looking at a sinus infection. If you think this is a sinus infection, you should seek urgent care.

25.title: Snoring
dlg: A person with obstructive sleep apnea start snoring heavily soon after falling asleep. The snoring gets louder and then interrupted by a long silent period during which there is no breathing. This is followed by a loud snort and gasp, as the person attempts to breathe. This pattern repeats itself.

0.header:
Snoring can happen to anyone and may not mean a health problem.

For instance, you may have neck weight putting pressure or narrowing the airways and you start to snore.


Before we send you to a pharmacist to discuss what you can use to stop snoring over the counter, let's make sure it is not something you will need a doctor's care for.

1.header: Do you start snoring heavily soon after falling asleep?

3.header:
Does the snoring get louder followed by a long silent period?

Then a loud snort and gasp that wakes you up?

Your partner will be able to tell you.

4.header:
Yes?
May be looking at obstructive sleep apnea going on here.

You should see a doctor for this.
(See "FYI" for a brief description)

5.header: In addition to this snoring, are you also having headaches that won't go away?

7.header:
In addition to the snoring do you fall asleep while working?

Or while watching TV?

8.header:
Seek medical help.
You may be looking at obstructive sleep apnea.

If not taken care of, you may experience:

  • depression or depression may get worse.
  • headaches that become hard to treat
  • increase in anxiety
  • loss of interest in sex
  • high blood pressure
  • risking job loss
  • heart arrhythmias.

9.header: Are you being forgetful lately since the snoring started?

10.header:
Yes?
You may be looking at obstructive sleep apnea.

Your snoring and sleep apnea is a problem and you should seek medical help.

If not taken care of you may:

  • fall into depression or depression may get worse
  • headaches that become hard to treat
  • increase in anxiety
  • loss of interest in sex
  • high blood pressure
  • risking job loss
  • heart arrhythmias

11.header:
Tried to rule out sleep apnea which will require doctor visit.

Do you use these at night?

  • Antihistamines
  • Sleep aids
  • Alcohol
  • Sedatives.

12.header:
Yes?
These can cause snoring. Stopping these may reduce your snoring.

13.header: Are you used to lying flat on your back while sleeping?

14.header:
Yes?
Avoid this. Sleep on your side, if possible.

Some doctors suggests sewing a golf or tennis ball to the back of your night clothes.

This will make you uncomfortable if you roll over and remind you to stay on your side. Eventually, sleeping on your side becomes a habit and you don't need a reminder.

15.header: Have you been treated for nasal polyps in the past?

16.header:
Yes?
These may have returned and can block the airways causing snoring.

17.header:
There are a lot of reasons while you may be snoring.

The top one is weight gain.

See if you can add aerobics to your weight loss regime and lose some weight.

20.header: On a scale of 1 to 10, how bad is this snoring?

0.header:
Coughing clears the large breathing passages of secretions, foreign particles, bacteria and viruses.

There are dry (no mucus) and productive (brings up mucus) cough.

Before you check with a pharmacist on what to take for this cough over-the-counter, let's make sure this is not an emergency or a serious situation.

1.header:
With this cough, are you experiencing shortness of breath?

Or difficulty breathing?

2.header:
Seek emergency room visit.

Here is why:

  • Need to rule out serious situation going on.

Note:
We do not advice continuing for now. You should only continue if you are not experiencing the question asked.

3.header: Did you break out in hives with this cough?

4.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • looking at a possible allergic reaction that can be dangerous.

5.header:
Are you also experiencing swollen face?

Or swollen throat?

6.header:
Seek urgent care or the emergency room.

Here is why:

  • looking at a possible allergic reaction that can be dangerous or a heart attack going on here.
  • Need to rule out a heart attack going on.

7.header: What about difficulty swallowing and you don't have a sore throat?

8.header:
Seek urgent care or the emergency room.

Here is why:

  • Possible anaphylactic reaction going on.

9.header: Does it feel like a tight band around the chest with this cough?

10.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • Symptom of a heart attack.

11.header:
Those were to rule out emergency situations.

Emergency situations that involve coughing include anaphylactic reactions and heart attack.

Let's continue and see how to take care of this cough of yours.

20.header: Do you also have fever with this cough?

21.header:
Seek urgent care or call your doctor.

Here is why:

  • You may be looking at a bacterial infection.

22.header: Are you coughing up blood?

23.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Especially if you are experiencing:

  • weight loss
  • fever
  • night sweats.

You may be looking at TB

24.header:
When breathing in, do you make high pitched sound?
(called stridor)

25.header:
Seek urgent care or call your doctor.

Here is why:

  • Stridor is a symptom, so the cause need to be found.
  • Possible anaphylactic reaction.
  • Possible swelling or severe fluid accumulation in the airways.

26.header: Do you cough up thick, foul-smelling, yellowish-green mucus?

27.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Possible bacteria infection
  • Need to rule out pneumonia.

28.header: Is this a violent cough that begins suddenly?

29.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Possible bronchitis
  • Possible spasm in the throat
  • Be prepared to go from doctor to doctor trying to find out the cause.

30.header:
Do you have a history of heart disease and your legs are swollen?

Or cough gets worse when you lie down?

31.header:
Seek emergency room or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • May be signs of congestive heart failure.

32.header:
Is this cough worse at night or in the early morning?

When you first wake up?

33.header:
Seek urgent care or call your doctor.

Here is why:

  • Possible acid reflux (GERD).

Suspect GERD especially if you also have burning chest or abdominal pain and a sour taste in the mouth when you wake up.

34.header: Is the cough dry (no mucus) or productive? (brings up mucus)

40.header:
Dry cough is an attempt to clear a foreign sensation in the throat.

This sensation can be a result of the throat and airways getting inflamed as in the beginning of a cold or flu or with inhaled pollens and so on.

Let's see what may be causing the dry cough.

41.header: Did you just start taking a new prescription medication?

42.header:
Yes?
See if your medication can cause cough by checking with your pharmacist.

50.header: What about heartburn or GERD. Do you get one often?

51.header:
Yes?
This can lead to dry cough.

52.header:
Seek urgent care or call your doctor.

Here is why:

  • Possible acid reflux (GERD).

Suspect GERD especially if you also have burning chest or abdominal pain and a sour taste in the mouth when you wake up.

60.header:
Symptom of respiratory infections, Allergies, and heart conditions.

If you have a cold or flu, it is usually in the middle of the illness as the throat is trying to get rid of all the mucus that has been produced.

It is important to thin the mucus and expectorate it (bring it up).

A thick mucus could accumulate and block the respiratory pathways.

Moreover, you want to bring it up and out rather than let it carry all the bacteria and viruses to the lungs thereby providing a risk for pneumonia.

Let's see if a pharmacist has any suggestions on what over-the-counter medications you can use to achieve this goals.

27.title: Sore Throat
dlg:
If the healthcare provider suspects mono, they will need to examine you and do some blood tests especially what is called a monotest.

This test looks for antibodies that form in the body during the infection, called heterophile antibodies.

If strep is the suspicion, then the doctor would have to do a rapid test or throat culture to test for strep.

This is the way to distinguish between infectious mono and strep throat.

Even, detection of streptococci in the throat area does not exclude infectious mononucleosis. The healthcare provider would have to make sure that your spleen is not enlarged. If it is, would have to rule in infectious mononucleosis and do some other tests.

0.header:
Sore throat can be caused by many things.

Such as:

  • Viruses
    (cold, flu and mononucleosis)
  • Bacteria
    (strep throat)
  • Allergies
    (pollens, pet dander, or molds)


Of these, the one most likely to cause serious complications is having a strep throat. Because if not treated on time, it may lead to kidney inflammation or rheumatic fever. Rheumatic fever can lead to a rash, inflamed joints and, in severe cases, damage to the valves of the heart.

With this in mind, let's get started.

1.header:
The top question regarding sore throat is usually:
"Is this a strep throat?"

Let's start with that.

Symptoms alone cannot diagnose strep throat. You will need a rapid test or throat culture to test for strep throat at the healthcare provider's office.

The earlier we send you to the doctor's office, the better for you and your family

Strep is contagious.

2.header: In addition to this sore throat, do you also have or had a fever?

10.header: Did this fever start suddenly?

12.header: Was this fever highest on the second day?

13.header:
Yes?
Hmmm. Start suspecting strep. Although not so fast.

14.header: Do you also have headache with this fever and sore throat?

15.header:
Yes?
This is a symptom of a strep throat infection.

16.header:
Fever of strep throat starts suddenly and ...

... Would be at its highest point on the second day.

Let's answer a few more questions and see if you may be looking at strep.

20.header:
Take a look at your tonsils in the mirror.

Are they red and swollen?

Turn on your device's camera lights to see better.

22.header: Are the lymph nodes in the neck swollen?

24.header:
Are you experiencing loss of appetite?

Or abnormal taste in the mouth?

26.header:
Using a mirror, look near the back of the throat towards the tonsils.

Any white or yellow spots on the throat and tonsils?

Note that, the throat can also appear bright red or dark red with spots on the roof of the mouth.

Turn on your device's camera lights so you can see better.

27.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Suspect strep throat.

28.header:
Look over the neck and chest region.

Any skin rash that was not there before?

29.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Suspect strep throat.

30.header:
Alright.
Those were symptoms of a strep throat infection.

If those apply to you, seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Let's rule out other things that can cause a sore throat which may need doctor visit if you don't think they apply to you.

Or do you think you should see a nearby urgent care clinic from the discussions so far?

40.header: Which of the symptoms listed below are you also experiencing right now?
40.except: Oops!, You told us nothing

41.header:
None of these?
Looking at a high probability of strep throat or infectious mononucleosis.

If all you have is just a sore throat and fever, let's continue to see if you are looking at strep throat or infectious mononucleosis.

42.header:
You may not be looking at a strep throat infection.

You may be looking at a cold or flu here.

Cough, laryngitis, and stuffy nose are not characteristic of strep throat infection. Their presence suggests another cause (usually viral or allergic).

If you feel it is a strep throat, visit the nearest urgent care clinic. Even if it comes out negative and it is a flu, you can still get started with flu treatment such as tamiflu.

Would you like to continue to see if you are looking at strep throat or infectious mononucleosis or see the nearest urgent care clinic to you?

50.header:
For strep or infectious mono, it is highly recommended you visit the nearest urgent care clinic or call the doctor.

You will need a rapid test or throat culture to test for strep throat.

This is one way to distinguish between infectious mono and strep throat.

Even, detection of streptococci in the throat area does not exclude infectious mononucleosis.

The doctor will have to make sure that your spleen is not enlarged. If it is, will probably rule in infectious mononucleosis and do some other tests.

Let's continue and see if we can rule out infectious mono for now.

51.header: Did the sore throat develop quickly (suddenly) or slowly (gradually) over time?

60.header: Did you have a fever that was highest on the second day?

61.header:
Yes?
This is a sign and symptom of a strep throat infection.

Strep symptoms include:

  • Sore throat that starts suddenly.
  • Fever highest on the second day.

62.header: Are you experiencing any chills?

63.header:
Yes?
This is a symptom of strep throat infection.

Strep symptoms include:

  • Sore throat that starts suddenly.
  • Fever highest on the second day.
  • Chills

64.header: Are you experiencing loss of appetite?

65.header:
Yes?
Suspect strep if you are experiencing the symptoms listed below.

Strep symptoms include:

  • Sore throat that starts suddenly.
  • Fever highest on the second day.
  • Chills
  • Loss of appetite

66.header:
If you answered "No" to the questions so far ...

You may not be looking at a strep throat infection.

Moving forward, we will assume that the sore throat started slowly or you are not sure how it all started.

70.header: Now, is the sore throat getting worse by the day?

72.header: Do you have a fever that normally peak in the afternoon or early evening?

73.header:
Yes?
Chances we are looking at infectious mono increasing.

Symptoms of infectious mono include:

  • Starting gradually.
  • Sore throat getting worse by the day.
  • Fever usually peaking in the afternoon or early evening.

74.header: Have you been feeling fatigued for a while now?

75.header:
Yes?
This is a sign and symptom of infectious mono.

Symptoms of infectious mono include:

  • Starting gradually.
  • Sore throat getting worse by the day.
  • Fever usually peaking in the afternoon or early evening.
  • Feeling fatigued for sometime.

76.header: Do you have tender lymph nodes along the back of the neck?

77.header:
Yes?
A symptom of infectious mono.

Symptoms of infectious mono include:

  • Starting gradually.
  • Sore throat getting worse by the day.
  • Fever usually peaking in the afternoon or early evening.
  • Feeling fatigued for sometime.
  • Tender lymph nodes along the back of the neck.

78.header: What about feeling drowsy? In addition to the sore throat and maybe fever.

79.header:
Yes?
This is a symptom of infectious mono.

Symptoms include:

  • Sore throat that started slowly.
  • Sore throat getting worse by the day.
  • Fever usually peaking in the afternoon or early evening.
  • Feeling fatigued for sometime.
  • Tender lymph nodes along the back of the neck.
  • Feeling drowsy

80.header: Are you experiencing muscle aches or stiffness?

81.header:
Yes?
There is usually muscle aches and stiffness with infectious mono.

82.header:
Those were to rule in or out strep throat or infectious mono.

If you suspect any of those two from the discussions above, you should visit the nearest urgent care clinic or your doctor's office as soon as possible.

Would you like to see what a pharmacist recommend you use over the counter to give you some relief for this sore throat?

Or you think you should see the nearest urgent care to you from the discussions so far?
